{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17618218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17618218"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:20:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:20:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16498"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16498"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.08,0,0.03,0.88]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9189"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68911"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9189"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16498"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54368"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5074"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21796"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22908"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68911"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with acute shortness of breath. She has a history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. On examination, she has widespread wheeze and increased work of breathing. She is prescribed a nebulised medication (ipratropium)  that blocks the effects of acetylcholine in the airways.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of ipratropium?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits phosphodiesterase enzyme","Blocks beta-2 adrenergic receptors","Stabilises mast cell membranes","Stimulates beta-2 adrenergic receptors","Competitively blocks muscarinic receptors"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIpratropium is an anticholinergic bronchodilator. Its primary mechanism of action involves \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompetitive inhibition of muscarinic acetylcholine receptors (M3 receptors)\u003C/strong\u003E in the airway smooth muscle. This blockade prevents acetylcholine-mediated bronchoconstriction, leading to bronchodilation and relief of symptoms such as wheezing and shortness of breath.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting phosphodiesterase enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide the rapid bronchodilation needed in this acute presentation. While methylxanthines like theophylline work through this mechanism, they have a slower onset of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking beta-2 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E would actually worsen this patient\u0027s bronchospasm and dyspnoea by promoting bronchoconstriction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStabilising mast cell membranes\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide immediate symptom relief in this acute situation as cromones are preventive medications rather than rescue therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulating beta-2 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E describes salbutamol, which is also used for acute bronchodilation but works through a different mechanism than the acetylcholine blockade mentioned in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIpratropium has a rapid onset of action and minimal systemic absorption, making it particularly useful for acute bronchodilation in conditions like chronic obstructive pulmonary disease and asthma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Short-acting anticholinergic drugs like ipratropium work by blocking muscarinic receptors in bronchial smooth muscle.","Blocking muscarinic receptors reduces bronchoconstriction and mucus secretion in the airways.","Ipratropium has minimal systemic effects due to poor absorption and is primarily used for acute bronchodilation."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54368"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16498"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54368"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T18:25:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T18:26:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9189"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68911"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"d